## [9] Conflict protocol
On rebase, Scratch squash, cherry-pick, or controlled-merge conflict:
1. Enter `PAUSED_CONFLICT`; never restart the workflow.
2. Identify actual operation, source, target/base, conflicted files, and preserved state.
3. Ask the user to choose collaborative conflict-by-conflict resolution or autonomous agent resolution.
4. Collaborative: explain competing intent per conflict and wait before editing it.
5. Autonomous: resolve against actual target architecture/current target-base behavior, run focused verification, and summarize decisions.
6. Stage only resolved paths. Raw `git add -- <paths>` is allowed solely because no source-CLI conflict-staging endpoint exists; `git add .` remains forbidden.
7. Continue through the source-CLI resume path.

Never assume every conflict rebases `develop`: hotfix uses its affected line, stabilization its release line, propagation its target line, and Scratch its official branch.
```text
🧭
Resume official ticket publication because the preserved operation can continue after exact conflicts are resolved.
GH workflow ticket publish --branch <official> --resume --push --create-pull-request
🧭
Resume Scratch transfer publication because the preserved squash-and-publish operation can continue after resolution.
GH workflow ticket publish --type <type> --subject "<subject>" [--target <official>] --resume --push --create-pull-request
🧭
Resume hotfix publication because the preserved correction can continue against its affected line after resolution.
GH workflow hotfix publish --branch <hotfix> --affected-line <line> --resume --push --create-pull-request
🧭
Resume stabilization publication because the preserved release workflow can continue after conflicts are resolved.
GH workflow release publish-stabilization --branch <branch> --release <release> --resume --push --create-pull-request
🧭
Resume target-line propagation because the preserved propagation workflow can continue after conflicts are resolved.
GH workflow hotfix propagate --source <hotfix> --target-line <line> --branch <fix-branch> --resume --push --create-pull-request
```
For a controlled published-branch merge conflict, resolve/stage exact paths, complete a governed merge with `commit create` using the branch ticket, rerun required checks, then return to publish. Never abort, take one side wholesale, or discard state without explicit authorization.

